We have been routine patrons of this nice restaurant for more than a decade.  It is easy to get there as it is right of the exit of Route 270 and off the street of Route 350 in the north of Gaithersburg. The environment is nice but the space will be crowed especially during the busy hours. It offers authentic Chinese dishes. Some of their specialty dishes are Chinese Northeastern styles. My favorite dish is 九层塔螺片 (Nine layer sea conch slides with basil leaves, which is originated from Taiwan I believe). The co-owner Mr. Deng is a very friendly fella who has a amazing memory.  Strongly recommend it if you are craving for a nice Chinese dinner.  It is suitable for family dinning or small party with less 10 people.

This is the spot if you want fresh-made and flavorful Chinese food, served by friendly and efficient staff. The chicken spring roll had exactly the right flavor and texture, with the wrapper crisp and light. The hot and sour soup was perhaps the best I've ever had, the spicy broth rich in flavor and full of bits of goodies. The shrimp with lobster sauce was FULL of shrimp that were PERFECTLY cooked, with a sauce with flavor that makes you remember every good Chinese meal you've ever had. They have a buffet, but we noticed that the regulars (of which there were obviously many!) all ordered off the menu. That would be our recommendation too.

Weekend mornings at 11:30am is when it begins, the cafeteria-style hot food bar serving everything from traditional Chinese donuts & soybean milk to veggies, steam buns, noodles, fried tofu, sesame cakes... So many options at a decent price point! Good for a chinese-style brunch fest if you're looking for more than just dim sum.  Because this part of the restaurant is mostly self-serve (you head to the front, choose your dishes, and pay in one go), service is a bit lacking and we had to pick up our own chopsticks. There is always the option for a sit-down meal and to order from their menu, which has a decent array of authentic dishes.

We tried this restaurant for the first time last night.  We ordered the vegetable spring rolls, chicken and broccoli and the vegetable lo mein and they were all very delicious. The meals were not oily as other restaurants have served. The vegetables in everything was very fresh. This is now our go to place for Chinese food. The restaurant restaurant is hidden in the back of Gaithersburg Square on the traffic circle end of the shopping center. It serves both American and traditional Chinese dishes. Highly recommend this place.

Chinese Turkey was great just like In "A Christmas Story" movie.. our plan to make a home cooked meal on Christmas (Eve) did not work out.. so we went upstairs. . Got dressed. . and everybody went out.. to eat.  Lo mein and the orange chicken here were great. . But my fave was the "Chinese Turkey".. aka. Duck in garlic sauce... (it came out from the kitchen with the head already removed.. not smiling at us)..  Lots of tender melt in your mouth duck breast..crispy skin in a savory. . Not fiery.. sauce with scallions. . Mmmmmm.  The wontons in the soup were light and yummy.. but the broth was weak.. a couple of spoonfuls of the delicious hot and sour soup added oomph to the won ton broth.  The spring rolls we ordered never arrived. The steamed rice was ok.  We started out at 5 pm. in a nearly empty restaurant just like In the movie.. (sans singing wait staff).. but by 6 pm.. the place was full..  90% of the clientele looked to be Asian.. and even to me seemed very authentic based on meals I enjoyed in Hong Kong.. recommended. Enjoy
